The '''Battle of the Duisburg Convoy''', also known as the '''Battle of the BETA Convoy''', was fought on the night of {{nowrap|8/9 November}} 1941 between an Italian [[convoy]], its escorts and four British ships. The convoy was named "BETA" by the Italian naval authorities and carried supplies for the Italian Army, civilian colonists and the {{lang|de|[[Afrika Korps]]}} in [[Italian Libya]]. The name "Duisburg Convoy" refers to the largest ship.

[[Force K]] of the [[Royal Navy]], based at Malta, annihilated the convoy, sinking all the merchant ships and the destroyer {{ship|Italian destroyer|Fulmine|1931|2}} with no loss and almost no damage. The {{sclass-|Maestrale|destroyer|1}} {{ship|Italian destroyer|Libeccio||2}} was sunk next day by the British submarine {{HMS|Upholder|P37|6}}, while picking up survivors.

The Italians were severely criticised by the German naval attaché and pressured to accept liaison officers at {{lang|it|[[Supermarina]]}} (headquarter of the {{lang|it|[[Regia Marina]]}}) and on its ships. Italian attempts to reduce the risk of interception by British forces, by sending individual ships, pairs and smaller convoys from several ports at once was futile, because the British were reading Italian naval codes; the next convoy was forced to return to port.

==Background==

===Italian belligerence===
The declaration of war by [[Italy]] on 10 June 1940 placed the Italian Royal Air Force ({{lang|it|[[Regia Aeronautica]]}}) astride the traditional British sea route to [[Indian Ocean]] ports via the Mediterranean and the Italian Royal Navy ({{lang|it|[[Regia Marina]]}}) roughly trebled the numbers of [[battleship]]s, [[cruiser]]s and [[submarine]]s available to the Axis against the [[Royal Navy]]. The British had held the eastern end of the Mediterranean and [[France]] the western end but the defection of France removed the [[French Navy]] from the Mediterranean on 25 June 1940. The British-based [[Force H]] at [[Gibraltar]] and the [[Mediterranean Fleet (United Kingdom)|Mediterranean Fleet]] at [[Alexandria]]. The island of Malta in the central Mediterranean was a base of operations for the British. Italy had [[Italian invasion of Egypt|invaded]] [[Egypt]] from [[Italian Libya]] ({{lang|it|Africa Settentrionale Italiana}}, ASI) in September 1940 and Greece in October 1940.{{sfn|Roskill|1957|pp=293–320}}

===1940–1941===
{{Location map+ |Libya |width=200 |float=right |caption={{centre|Libya location map}} |places=
{{Location map~ |Libya |lat=32.902222 |long=13.185833 |label=[[Tripoli]] |label_size=100 |position=left |marksize=8}}
{{Location map~ |Libya |lat=32.116667 |long=20.066667 |label=[[Benghazi]] |label_size=100 |position=left |marksize=8}}
}}
In early November 1940, the Italian offensive in Greece had been defeated and the Italian battleships {{ship|Italian battleship|Littorio||2}}, {{ship|Italian battleship|Conte di Cavour||2}} and {{ship|Italian battleship|Caio Duilio||2}} had been damaged at the [[Battle of Taranto]]. The ship losses of the Italian Fleet had made it easier for the British to supply Malta and Greece.{{sfn|Greene|Massignani|2002|pp=56–114}} The [[Axis powers|Axis]] forces involved the [[Western Desert Campaign]] were supplied across the Mediterranean by convoys from Italy to the ASI. [[Tripoli]] was the main {{lang|fr|[[entrepôt]]}} of the colony, which had lesser ports to the east, including [[Benghazi]].{{sfn|Stegemann|2015|pp=717–718}} The normal route for Italian supply deliveries to Libya went about {{cvt|600|mi|km|0}} westwards around Sicily and then close to the coast of [[Tunisia]] to Tripoli, to avoid interference from British aircraft, ships and submarines based at Malta. In Africa, supplies had to be carried huge distances by road or in small consignments by coaster. The distance from Tripoli to Benghazi was about {{cvt|650|mi|km}}.{{sfn|Cooper|1978|pp=361–362}}

==={{lang|de|Unternehmen Sonnenblume}}===
{{Main|Operation Compass|Operation Sonnenblume}}

In early 1941, after [[Operation Compass]], the big British and Commonwealth victory in Egypt and Cyrenaica, the best-equipped units in XIII Corps went to Greece as part of [[Operation Lustre]]. [[Adolf Hitler]] responded to the Italian disaster with Directive 22 (11 January) ordering {{lang|de|Unternehmen Sonnenblume}} (Operation Sunflower), the deployment of a new {{lang|de|Deutsches Afrika Korps}} (DAK) to Libya, as a barrier detachment ({{lang|de|Sperrverband}}). The DAK had fresh troops with better tanks, equipment and air support than the surviving Italian forces in the ASI.{{sfn|Stegemann|2015|pp=654–656}} The Axis force raided and quickly defeated the British at El Agheila on 24 March and at [[Brega|Mersa el Brega]] on 31 March, exploited the success and by 15 April, had pushed the British back to the Libyan–Egyptian border at Sollum and besieged Tobruk.{{sfn|Stegemann|2015|pp=673–684}} Several Axis attempts to seize Tobruk failed and the front line settled on the Egyptian border into November 1941.{{sfn|Playfair|2004|pp=153–159}}

===Malta===
From 1 June to 31 October 1941, British forces based at Malta sank about {{cvt|220000|LT|t|0}} of Axis shipping on the African convoy routes, {{cvt|94000|LT|t|0}} by the navy and {{cvt|115000|LT|t|0}} by [[Royal Air Force]] (RAF) and [[Fleet Air Arm]] (FAA) aircraft from Malta and Egypt. Loaded Axis ships sailing to Africa accounted for 90 percent of the losses and Malta-based squadrons were responsible for about 75 percent of ships sunk by aircraft.{{sfn|Richards|Saunders|1975|pp=169–170}}{{sfn|Playfair|2004|pp=324–325}} In October 1941 the British re-established a flotilla of surface ships at Malta ([[Force K]]) for the first time since April and a force of [[Fairey Swordfish]] torpedo bombers. Italian air reconnaissance discovered the ships on 21 October and cancelled sailings for Tripoli, leaving only the inferior facilities at Benghazi open.{{sfn|Stegemann|2015|p=718}}

==Prelude==
===Duisburg (BETA) Convoy operation===

The convoy consisted two German vessels, SS ''Duisburg'' 7,889 [[gross register tonnage]] (GRT) and SS ''San Marco'' (3,113 GRT) and the Italian MV ''Maria'' (6,339 GRT), SS ''Sagitta'' (5,153 GRT) and MV ''Rina Corrado'' (5,180 GRT), carrying 389 vehicles, {{cvt|34473|LT|t|0}} of munitions, fuel in barrels and troops for the Italian and German forces in Libya. The tankers ''Conte di Misurata'' (7,599 GRT) and ''Minatitlan'' (5,014 GRT) carried {{cvt|17281|LT|t|0}} of fuel.{{sfn|O'Hara|2009|p=171}} A powerful escort was to arranged for the convoy operation to counter the British flotilla recently based at Malta.{{sfn|Greene|Massignani|2002|p=194}}

